PARTI Islam Se-Malaysia (PAS) Kawasan Putatan meneruskan Budaya Politik Matang dan Sejahtera (BPMS) dengan mengunjungi 28 buah sekolah di sekitar Putatan, Tanjung Aru dan Sembulan.
Kunjungan dibuat selama dua hari. Hari pertama diketuai oleh Ustaz Amiruddin Mohd Rosdi, Ketua Penerangan PAS Putatan, Arwin Azhad, Ketua Lajnah Perpaduan Nasional bersama AJK Dewan Muslimat PAS Putatan. Turut bersama, Zulzaiem Himee, Ketua Pemuda PAS Negeri Sabah.
Serahan kek sempena sambutan Hari Guru di setiap sekolah antaranya, SK Tansau, SMK Tansau, SK Putatan, SK Kg. Contoh, SK Stella Maris, SM La Salle, Maktab Sabah, SK Sembulan, SMK Sanzac, Tadika JHEAINS, SK Tanjung Aru 2 dan Pondok An-Nur Pasir Putih.
Hari kedua, Ustaz Abu Nuha, Yang Dipertua PAS Putatan yang baru kembali dari Indonesia turun padang bersama meneruskan kunjungan dan serahan kek. Antara sekolah yang dikunjungi ialah, SK Pulau Gaya, SMK Pulau Gaya, SK Kem Lok Kawi, SK Petagas, SAN Integrasi Putatan, Masrasah al-Khariah dan Madrasah as-Salam.
Para guru yang ditemui sangat berbesar hati menyambut kedatangan PAS Putatan seterusnya mengucapkan terima kasih atas ingatan dan perhargaan yang diberikan.
Program seumpama ini adalah takwim tahunan PAS Putatan yang sentiasa prihatin dan menghargai usaha dan pengorbanan para pendidik dan warga guru dalam membina sahsiah dan jati diri generasi kepimpinan negara. Ini bertepatan dengan tema "Guru Pembentuk Generasi Rabbani".
PAS Putatan berharap para guru meneruskan dedikasi dan perjuangan mendidik anak watan. Semoga segala usaha dan titik peluh diganjari oleh Allah dengan sebaik-baik ganjaran, tegas Ustaz Abu Nuha.  HARAKAHDAILY 18/5/2017
HARAKAH DAILY
22 Jalan Pahang Barat,Off Jalan Pahang,53000 Kuala Lumpur
Tel : 603 4023 3270Fax : 603 4023 3278
IPOH: The 216 students placed in isolation for fear of having the avian flu were found to have just regular influenza, said health authorities.
Its just seasonal flu and not H1N1 as suspected, said Perak Health Committee chairman Datuk Dr Mah Hang Soon.
One hundred and twenty-seven students were quarantined at the hostel dormitory of Sekolah Raja Perempuan Taayah after there was an outbreak of flu-like symptoms at several schools in the state earlier this month.
Eighty-four others were isolated at the Sekolah Tuanku Abdul Rahman hostel.
Two more students, diagnosed early with plain influenza, were ordered to rest at home.
It was the same with the three at SK Klebang and they were also sent home.
Dr Mah visited some of the students yesterday and many told him they were feeling better despite still having a fever, sore throat and cough.
He expects them to improve in the next few days.
Flu patients normally get well after about five to seven days, he added.
According to him, one group likely got infected in class.
I was told by the school that the teacher was sick. Its possible the students might have got it from the teacher, he said.
He said those in another school probably got the flu during a football tournament on Sunday.
In Petaling Jaya, Health director-general Datuk Dr Noor Hisham Abdullah urged the public not to panic over the illnesses.
He advised those showing the symptoms not to go to work or attend school.
Tests would be carried out to find out the cause of the outbreak in Perak, he said.
