TUARAN: Kementerian Pendidikan akan menangani segera isu kekurangan sekolah menengah yang menjejaskan penduduk kawasan luar bandar, termasuk projek sekolah terbengkalai akibat faktor tapak di Sabah.
Ia termasuk projek pembinaan Sekolah Menengah Kebangsaan (SMK) Pekan Nabalu, di sini, yang terbengkalai sejak tahun 2014 selepas Jabatan Geosains dan Mineral mendapati tapak sekolah terbabit tidak selamat kerana berlaku pergerakan dalam bumi.
Menteri Pendidikan, Datuk Seri Mahdzir Khalid, berkata projek bernilai RM30 juta itu yang pembinaannya dimulakan pada tahun 2012 dan mencapai 20 peratus siap pada tahun 2014 terpaksa dihentikan.
Katanya, situasi itu melambatkan proses menyiapkan sekolah menengah yang bakal menampung keperluan 15 sekolah rendah di sekitar Zon Nabalu, di sini, berikutan perlu mencari tapak baharu yang sesuai.
"Kerajaan sudah membayar kira-kira RM5 juta kepada kontraktor bagi projek pembinaan sekolah itu tetapi atas faktor keselamatan, ia dihentikan menyebabkannya terbengkalai.
"Bagaimanapun, kita sudah mengenal pasti tapak baharu seluas kira-kira sembilan hektar berhampiran Sekolah Kebangsaan (SK) Giok, di sini.
"Kerja pembinaan akan dimulakan selepas semua proses, termasuk reka bentuk bangunan diselesaikan," katanya kepada pemberita selepas melawat tapak baharu sekolah menengah berkenaan, di sini, hari ini.
Yang turut hadir ialah Menteri Sains, Teknologi dan Inovasi, Datuk Madius Tangau; Pengerusi Lembaga Pelancongan Sabah, Datuk Joniston Bangkuai dan Timbalan Ketua Pengarah Pelajaran, Datuk Dr Amin Senin.
Sementara itu, Madius yang juga Ahli Parlimen Tuaran, berkata tapak baharu sekolah itu yang berstatus tanah hak adat anak negeri (NCR) akan diserahkan kepada Kementerian Pendidikan selepas semua penduduk yang menuntut hak terhadap tanah terbabit menandatangani surat kebenaran penyerahan tanah.
"Setakat ini, ada lima lagi penduduk belum menandatanganinya. Kita berharap pihak kampung dapat menyelesaikan perkara ini segera supaya projek pembinaan semula sekolah menengah ini dapat dimulakan secepat mungkin," katanya.
Selain melawat tapak baharu SMK Pekan Nabalu, Mahdzir dan Madius turut melawat pelaksanaan Projek Perintis Inisiatif Pendidikan Sains Berasaskan Inkuiri (IBSE) di SK Mengkabong dan menghadiri Dialog Transformasi Nasional 2050 (TN50) di SK Lokos, Kiulu, di sini.
2017  BH Online | New Straits Times Press (M) Berhad (4485-H) | Hak Cipta Terpelihara
KUALA LUMPUR: "Kassim Selamat? Siapa dia Kassim Selamat? Lawyer, Magistrate? Ahli muzik? Memang pantang datuk nenek aku ahli muzik".
Remember this famous quote from late Tan Sri P. Ramlee's Ibu Mertuaku film, when one of the main characters, Nyonya Mansoor found out that her daughter wanted to marry musician Kassim Selamat?
Such sentiment against artistic talents was shared by many parents in Malaysia for decades, who believed that it was a somewhat useless gift that would not yield a good future.
However, the age of sidelining arts is today something of the past.
In its way forward, the Education Ministry (MoE) has since 2007 given due recognition to the importance of developing artistic talents among students.
That year, it set up two Sekolah Seni Malaysia (SSeM) in Sarawak and Johor.
Now, the number of MoE art schools has expanded to five, with three others established in Kuala Lumpur, Perak and Sabah.
MoE Co-Curriculum and Arts Division assistant director Zulkafli Abu Hassan said these schools have produced over 1,000 students who have completed their secondary school learning and SPM.
He said the art schools were set up to hone their talents while at the same time learning the same subjects as other secondary schools.
"In SSeM, students start enrolment from Form 1 where they have to take PT3 core subjects, and on top of that, four art subjects - Theatre, Music, Dance and Visual Art.
"After PT3, the students will go into Science, Art or Accounting streams, among others, and an artistic subject of their choice," he said when met at MOE's exhibition booth during the Umno General Assembly 2016 in the Putra World Trade Centre, here earlier today.
The students can choose either to take the Theatre, Music, Dance or from three divisions of Visual Arts - Design, Fine Arts and Visual Communications.
"SSeM requires all students to excel in their study, while they polish their talents at the same time.
"Joining art school does not mean that a student can only go for art courses after finishing school or only venture into art-related jobs."
At the booth, the New Straits Times met 13-year-old Mohd Muizzuddin Mohd Nurul Azmi who was flaunting his portrait-drawing skills for the assembly's visitors to see.
Muizzuddin, who had just completed his Form 1 at SSeM Perak, said while he was good in drawing portraits, his ambition is to follow the footsteps of his architect mother.
"My parents started seeing my talent in drawing since I was in Standard Three, and they were very supportive when I said I wanted to join SSeM.
"In the school, I have learnt a lot on how to improve my drawing skills and other artistic subjects as well. It is very interesting as SSeM allows me to excel in my study and at the same time let me do something that I love," said the second from four siblings, who hails from Ipoh, Perak.
Muizzuddin's teacher Mohamad Izwan Mohd Saad said parents who are interested to enrol their children in SSeM can fill an online form available at MOE's website (www.moe.gov.my).
He said the enrolment opening starts in June every year, followed by an interview.
2017  New Straits Times.
Sekolah kebangsaan kini menjadi mono-etnik berbanding masa lalu yang lebih kepelbagaian, keluh Ketua Pemuda Umno Wilayah Persekutuan, Datuk Mohd Razlan Mohammad Rafii.
Semasa sesi dialog TN50 di Titiwangsa semalam, beliau menyambut baik cadangan peserta yang menggesa pengenalan sekolah satu aliran yang memelihara identiti kepelbagaian kaum di Malaysia.
"Semasa saya kecil dan masuk sekolah kebangsaan, dalam kelas ada 20 hingga 30 pelajar Cina, 20 hingga 30 orang pelajar Melayu dan 20 hingga 30 pelajar India.
"Tetapi apa yang berlaku hari ini? Di sekolah kebangsaan, 90 peratus daripada satu kaum; hanya satu kaum masuk sekolah jenis kebangsaan Cina dan satu lagi kaum ke sekolah jenis kebangsaan Tamil. Adakah (perkembangan) ini baik untuk negara kita?
"Mungkin kita boleh ada apa (peserta Yasser Arafat) katakan tadi. Mungkin semua kaum duduk di bawah satu bumbung, tanpa mengancam identiti mereka," jelas beliau kepada penonton.
Turut hadir sebagai ahli panel pada sesi dialog itu ialah Ahli Parlimen Titiwangsa Datuk Johari Abdul Ghani.
Terdahulu, seorang peserta yang memperkenalkan diri sebagai Yasser Arafat mencadangkan sekolah satu aliran sebagai sebahagian daripada aspirasi Malaysia pada tahun 2050, tetapi masih mengekalkan identiti pelbagai kaum di Malaysia.
